author: Russell Brand
description:
Political labels like “fascist,” “communist,” and even “terrorist” have become floating weapons rather than descriptions, hurled and withdrawn as Trump, Mamdani, Maddow, Cheney and others rearrange themselves inside the same small club of power. When Kamala Harris and Rachel Maddow turn up at Dick Cheney’s funeral, and a man Trump calls a “communist lunatic” happily calls Trump a “fascist” days after a cordial meeting, it exposes how empty these labels now are as markers of principle. Marjorie Taylor Greene’s resignation and apology for toxic politics, alongside her breaks on war funding and Epstein transparency, hint at something more dangerous to the system than partisan outrage: an individual stepping outside the script and exposing how much of our “ideology” is really conditioning. The real question isn’t whether someone is left or right, but who writes the roles we’re all expected to play—and what happens when we refuse.
[UNPACKED]
